<sections><clause id="_the_relation_between_the_numbers_iim_r_and_iib_j" obligation="normative">
<title>The relation between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></title>
<p id="_b3c3ae70-4905-e4bd-f3e2-0d2f6336217d">In our recent study <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> on alternate sums of powers of integers, i.e. of sums of the type</p>

<formula id="eq1"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mtext> with </mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_d0c26d69-63a5-fda2-a991-905ddcf3ab3e">it was shown that they can be expressed in the form</p>

<formula id="eq2"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_b1588164-4122-9fec-f3a2-69cee2de534a">where <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></stem> is given by the number of terms in <xref target="eq1"/>, while <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are coefficients that have been tabulated.</p>

<p id="_8aa8abc5-3cf7-59f9-fdbb-0060b4581b0c">We found that these coefficients can be expressed by the “basic” integers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≡</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem>, since</p>

<formula id="eq3"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msup><mi>r</mi><mo>!</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>!</mo><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>!</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mtext> for </mtext><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>j</mi></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_a556e4d7-cf2a-bbf4-e6cc-cd7b624c6d47">The alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/>, written in powers of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>, thus begins for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> even with</p>

<formula id="eq4"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>μ</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_bc4b10b7-8130-1a1b-3776-a7ad9e940890">whereas for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> odd there is no term proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>.</p>

<p id="_9b353682-7b07-d5d0-a88a-f464b48dff7e">It appears that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> play a role similar to that of the well-known Bernoulli numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> which occur in the study of the sums</p>

<formula id="eq5"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>≡</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_7c7f55be-5a30-a345-a6a9-ba12d41215dc">Some similarities between the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> have already been noted in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>, but it has not been possible to establish a clear link between the two series. It is the purpose of the present Note to make up for this deficiency. Some familiarity with <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> will make the reading easier.</p>

<p id="_62e1cdb8-3dfd-c7f2-d321-ddd2d56caa8f">The idea is to use the fact that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem>, as shown in <xref target="eq4"/>. If we can subdivide <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> into a sum of contributions of type <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and determine the coefficients of the linear terms <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> (in which the Bernoulli numbers occur), it must be possible to obtain the required relation by comparison of the respective coefficients.</p>

<p id="_6a18ad0a-dbda-8276-aa1e-8634e5380f22">Let us begin by decomposing the alternate sum <xref target="eq1"/> in a suitable way — the very  rearrangement we tried to avoid in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. Since <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi></math></stem> is even, we can put <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>n</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math></stem>. Then</p>

<formula id="eq6"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>j</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_24dff6cb-c193-59de-9a0c-fcc4e6e685b3" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow></munderover><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_ee1dde97-68f9-0285-8d75-148e7634de10" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_1464ef96-7651-4248-63a1-12e9249dcd2d" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_18640f1c-49b6-7a05-bf51-b9995c41f003">Let us now look at the development of a Bernoullian sum <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>. From relation (23) given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/> we conclude that, for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>2</mn></math></stem> and even,</p>

<formula id="eq7"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mi>t</mi><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_649fde06-a2f1-a662-7036-cfa570b4baba">We note in passing that <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi></math></stem> odd has no terms proportional to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> as the development stops at <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></stem>, exactly as for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>.</p>

<p id="_53a9a873-9e61-226b-c713-db8f1acd697a">The two cases with <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></stem> appearing in <xref target="eq6"/> have to be treated separately. One finds</p>

<formula id="eq8"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>t</mi></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_ddb95597-c09a-e5cf-9138-c2b11309256d">and</p>

<formula id="_cc948f5c-e639-b15b-61fd-957283e43c6b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>.</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_d88ac9e2-1cae-757e-8212-af0be9a51f6c">A look at <xref target="eq4"/> shows that the value of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> can be obtained from <xref target="eq6"/> by assembling the coefficients of <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>t</mi></math></stem> appearing in <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem>. Writing <xref target="eq6"/> as</p>

<formula id="eq9"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mo>ℤ</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>k</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mtext/></mrow><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>S</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_ce0c15bb-ca23-dbd5-1029-9c6ba837d654">we find, with <xref target="eq7"/> and <xref target="eq8"/>,</p>

<formula id="eq10"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_c95b14f6-8aa6-28b6-3c21-198d91cb334b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext>, (even)</mtext></mrow></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mi>r</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math></stem></formula>

<p id="_31ffb0c0-a450-9507-cd4e-9c4ac9e99b61">This is the relation looked for. It shows that the two series of numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> and <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> are indeed closely linked, and relation <xref target="eq10"/> is even somewhat reminiscent of the recurrence formula (18) found previously in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. It may be worthwhile noting that the sum in <xref target="eq10"/> yields an even integer.</p>

<p id="_3d8bab65-0f28-3ca9-6ddd-7ad1475ba6b2">Let us check (10) with three practical applications.</p>

<ul id="_6db2c6ea-dec1-bbad-5138-292773365c8e"><li><p id="_100c8c78-5303-4785-83a7-f6163d3b2123">For = 8:</p>
<formula id="_26a04941-7df7-89da-3f7a-2a76e2722f3b" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_36726a0f-7c1c-679b-98e9-bf4d0f7b9cb6" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>−</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mn>8</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></math></stem></formula>

<formula id="_181287b2-ddfd-55b9-27cb-68e789aa2874" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>−</mo><mfenced open="[" close="]"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mn>28</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>16</mn><mn>70</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mrow><mn>64</mn><mn>28</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>42</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>;</mo></math></stem></formula>
</li>
<li><p id="_c067ae69-145a-0911-40bf-d6baaffe4486">for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math></stem> :</p>
<formula id="_081c8686-a643-f4ca-ebad-51436d6d1039" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>10</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>155</mn><mo>;</mo></math></stem></formula>
</li>
<li><p id="_25c1008a-90ff-5d5f-265d-f45fd5c58bb9">for <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math></stem> :</p>
<formula id="_0f727ce5-3aae-8a05-7842-9df131cef448" unnumbered="true"><stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>−</mo><munderover><mrow><mo>∑</mo></mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow></munderover><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msup><mfenced open="(" close=")"><mtable><mtr><mtd><mn>12</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>j</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>…</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mtext> </mtext><mn>073</mn></math></stem></formula>
</li>
</ul>

<p id="_cbef5634-add7-a036-1b11-ce078d15352d">All these results agree with the numerical values given in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>.</p>

<p id="_258d50bc-4ff5-bca9-2d01-73337c8ce6cd">Obviously, the existence of the new relation <xref target="eq10"/> does not me an that the numbers <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>M</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow></msub></math></stem> become superfluous; their practical usefulness is obvious in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="muller" citeas="[1]"/>. In any case, <xref target="eq10"/> is a very useful tool for their numerical evaluation, since it is a simple relation making use only of the Bernoulli numbers, which are readily available in tabular form, for example up to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mstyle mathvariant="italic"><mi>B</mi></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>60</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> in <eref type="inline" bibitemid="abramowitz" citeas="[2]"/>.</p>
